                <h3>My Story in a Nutshell</h3>
                <p>
                    As a child I instinctively knew that an audience will focus better when given a “visual aid.” This led me to spend many more hours drawing elaborate posters than writing the book reports accompanying them. I continued creating fine art and concert posters through my music and liberal arts studies (see Education section above), and when a case of elbow tendinitis derailed my music career, I took a wild leap into the field of design. After a fantastic four years as a product designer at the American Museum of Natural History, I desired more training and entered an AAS program at Parsons. There, I became intrigued by interactive design and user experience. Since then I’ve found a happy home in creating impactful, delightful “visual aids” within the data-driven parameters of good UX. My positions at BN.com, scholastic.com, and marvel.com, have given me complex, fascinating experiences, and I’m now eager to take on the most extreme UX and design challenges. <a href="http://buttersdesign.com/#about">Read more on my About Page</a>.
